  "text": "Cyclin G1 is activated in response to DNA damage that is mediated by doxorubicin, leading to increase of cell population in G2/M phase [CITATION_1] . So that, in our study there was an increase in G2/M phase (10.60%) in case of Our results showed an increase in G 0 /G1-phase population (85%) and an increase in G2/M phase (9%) in HepG2 cells transfected with miR-122 mimics then treated with doxorubicin (miR-122/Dox) as compared to inhibitor negative control (NC). Depending on the above discussed for cell cycle distribution analysis; we can explain our results in case of treatment of HepG2 cells with miR-122 mimics then with doxorubicin. MiR-122 restoration in HepG2 cells has increased the percentage of cells in G 0 / G1-phase (85%) while decreasing the percentage of cells in G2/M phase through targeting cyclin G1 gene. Then treatment with doxorubicin, DNA damaging agent, leading to reactivation of cyclin G1 and increased the accumulation of cells in G2/M phase (9%).",
